  "signature": "ed25519:2a7f59be5ea45872568c29496d6b5c04dab74ed57dab443a7de901a1cbd47a4efcb30c8007848e9ce8adb584bc8d8eb2134b58885eb908f3f128507168e89709",
  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 5,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/sqa-mrl5",
      "rationale": "The CFD solver (ANSYS Fluent 2023 R2) is operated under a validated software quality assurance plan conforming to FDA guidance on software validation. The SQA plan includes version-controlled source code, automated regression test suite (>2400 test cases), documented change-control procedures, and independent third-party audit completed in Q3 2024. All solver patches applied during this study were regression-tested prior to use. SQA documentation package archived at https://uofa.net/morrison/evidence/sqa-audit-2024. Achieved level 5 exceeds the required level 4 for MRL 5."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 5,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/code-verification-mrl5",
      "rationale": "Numerical code verification was performed using the Method of Manufactured Solutions (MMS) for the Navier-Stokes solver, turbulence transport equations, and the power-law hemolysis damage model. Observed order of accuracy matched theoretical order (2nd-order spatial, 1st-order temporal) to within 2% for all solution variables across three mesh refinement levels. MMS test cases archived at https://uofa.net/morrison/evidence/mms-verification-2024. Independent reproduction of MMS results confirmed by external reviewer. Achieved level 5."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
      "achievedLevel": 5,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/discretization-error-mrl5",
      "rationale": "A systematic mesh convergence study was conducted across four mesh densities (2.1M, 5.8M, 14.2M, and 31.7M cells) following the ASME V&V 20 Grid Convergence Index (GCI) methodology. The fine-grid GCI for the normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) quantity of interest was 1.3%, well below the 5% threshold. Richardson extrapolation yielded an asymptotic ratio of 1.02, confirming convergence in the asymptotic range. Temporal convergence was verified with three time-step sizes; the selected time step yielded a temporal GCI of 0.4%. All discretization error data linked at https://uofa.net/morrison/data/mesh-convergence-study and https://uofa.net/morrison/validation/vr-05-mesh-convergence."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 5,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/test-conditions-mrl5",
      "rationale": "Experimental test conditions were instrumented and documented to ISO/IEC 17025 standards. Blood analog fluid properties (viscosity, density) were measured at each test session using calibrated rheometer and densitometer with NIST-traceable standards. Flow rates were measured with Coriolis mass flow meters (±0.2% accuracy). Rotational speed was servo-controlled and verified with optical tachometer. Temperature was maintained at 37 ± 0.5°C throughout all hemolysis experiments. Inlet velocity profiles were measured by PIV and used as boundary conditions in the CFD model. Full test condition documentation archived at https://uofa.net/morrison/evidence/test-conditions-2024."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
      "achievedLevel": 5,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/output-comparison-mrl5",
      "rationale": "Quantitative output comparison was performed using the validation metric of ASME V&V 20, computing the validation uncertainty Uval and comparing the model-experiment discrepancy E against Uval. For the primary QoI (NIH), |E| = 0.0031 g/100L versus Uval = 0.0048 g/100L, confirming model adequacy at the 95% confidence level. Secondary QoIs (pressure rise, velocity profiles at 12 cross-sections) all passed the V&V 20 adequacy criterion. Detailed comparison tables and Bland-Altman plots are provided in the validation report at https://uofa.net/morrison/evidence/output-comparison-report-2024. Linked to ValidationResult vr-01 through vr-04."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 5,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/qoi-relevance-mrl5",
      "rationale": "The primary QoI (normalized index of hemolysis, NIH) is the FDA-recognized metric for blood pump hemolysis assessment per the FDA Guidance on Assessing the Credibility of Computational Modeling and Simulation (2023). NIH is directly linked to the clinical endpoint (plasma-free hemoglobin elevation) and is the quantity used in the regulatory decision criterion. A formal QoI relevance mapping document traces NIH through the clinical risk pathway to patient harm, confirming that the selected QoI is both necessary and sufficient for the regulatory decision. Secondary QoIs (shear stress distribution, exposure time histogram) are linked to mechanistic hemolysis model inputs, providing traceability from simulation outputs to the damage model. Documentation at https://uofa.net/morrison/evidence/qoi-relevance-mapping-2024."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 5,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/validation-relevance-mrl5",
      "rationale": "A formal validation relevance assessment was conducted using the ASME V&V 40 validation hierarchy framework. The validation experiments used the same FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry as the COU model, operated across the same five flow-speed operating points specified in the COU. Blood analog fluid (porcine blood, hematocrit 30 ± 2%) matches the COU clinical population. The validation dataset spans the full operating envelope of the COU including the worst-case hemolysis point identified in COU1. A validation relevance matrix documenting geometry similarity, fluid similarity, operating condition overlap, and QoI alignment is archived at https://uofa.net/morrison/evidence/validation-relevance-matrix-2024. No significant gaps between validation and COU conditions were identified."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/solver-error-mrl5",
      "rationale": "Iterative convergence was monitored for all simulations using residual norms and QoI monitors. All simulations achieved residual convergence to 1e-6 for continuity and momentum equations and 1e-8 for turbulence quantities before data extraction. QoI monitors (NIH, pressure rise) were confirmed stable to within 0.1% over the final 500 iterations. Round-off error was assessed by comparing double-precision and quad-precision results for two representative cases; differences were below 0.01% for all QoIs. Iterative and round-off error contributions were included in the total numerical uncertainty budget. Solver error documentation archived at https://uofa.net/morrison/evidence/solver-error-assessment-2024."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 5,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/use-error-mrl5",
      "rationale": "Use error was controlled through a formal simulation execution protocol requiring independent review of all model setup files (geometry, mesh, boundary conditions, solver settings, post-processing scripts) by a second qualified analyst prior to each simulation run. A simulation execution checklist was completed and signed for every production run. Automated input-file consistency checks were run prior to solver invocation. All boundary condition values were cross-referenced against the instrumented test condition records. Post-processing scripts were verified against hand calculations for three representative cases. Use error control documentation archived at https://uofa.net/morrison/evidence/use-error-protocol-2024."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
      "achievedLevel": 5,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/model-form-mrl5",
      "rationale": "Model form uncertainty was assessed through a structured model-form sensitivity study comparing three turbulence model formulations (SST k-ω, realizable k-ε, and RSM) and two hemolysis damage model formulations (Giersiepen-Wurzinger power law and Zhang modified power law). The SST k-ω model with Zhang hemolysis model produced the best agreement with experimental data (minimum validation discrepancy) and was selected as the production model. Model-form uncertainty was quantified as the spread across formulations and incorporated into the total uncertainty budget. A formal model-form assessment report is archived at https://uofa.net/morrison/evidence/model-form-assessment-2024. The selected model form is justified by both predictive accuracy and physical fidelity arguments."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
      "achievedLevel": 5,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/model-inputs-mrl5",
      "rationale": "A comprehensive model input uncertainty characterization was performed for all 18 identified uncertain input parameters, including fluid viscosity, density, inlet velocity profile, rotational speed, pump geometry tolerances, and hemolysis model coefficients. Probability distributions were assigned to each input based on measured calibration data or literature meta-analysis. A Monte Carlo uncertainty propagation study with 10,000 model evaluations (using a validated surrogate model calibrated against 120 full-fidelity CFD runs) was used to propagate input uncertainties to the NIH QoI. The 95th percentile NIH prediction including all input uncertainties remained below the regulatory acceptance threshold. Input uncertainty data archived at https://uofa.net/morrison/data/uq-monte-carlo-10k-runs."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 5,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/test-samples-mrl5",
      "rationale": "Validation experiments were conducted using n=8 independent pump specimens manufactured to production tolerances, with three replicate hemolysis runs per specimen (n=24 total experimental observations per operating point). Specimen-to-specimen geometric variability was characterized by CMM measurement and confirmed to be within design tolerance. Blood samples were sourced from a single donor pool per test session and hematocrit was adjusted to 30 ± 2% for all runs. Plasma-free hemoglobin was measured using a validated spectrophotometric assay (CV < 3%). The sample size provides 90% statistical power to detect a 10% difference in NIH at α=0.05. Test sample documentation archived at https://uofa.net/morrison/evidence/test-samples-2024."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 5,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/input-equivalency-mrl5",
      "rationale": "A formal equivalency assessment was conducted comparing all model input parameters against the corresponding experimentally measured values used in the validation campaign. Inlet boundary conditions were derived directly from PIV-measured velocity profiles at the pump inlet plane. Fluid properties were matched to within measurement uncertainty. Rotational speed was matched to within 0.3 RPM. Pump geometry was reconstructed from CMM measurements of the validation specimens and confirmed to match the CAD model to within 15 μm. A parameter equivalency table documenting each input, its simulation value, its experimental value, and the equivalency justification is archived at https://uofa.net/morrison/evidence/input-equivalency-table-2024. No significant equivalency gaps were identified. Sobol sensitivity indices (archived at https://uofa.net/morrison/data/sensitivity-sobol-indices) confirm that all top-ranked influential inputs are equivalently characterized."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/decision/cou2-mrl5-accepted-2026",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/morrison/org/computational-biofluid-lab",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "The credibility assessment for the COU2 CFD hemolysis model at MRL 5 is accepted based on the following structured evidence review. All 13 ASME V&V 40 credibility factors have been assessed and all achievedLevels meet or exceed the requiredLevels for MRL 5. The primary QoI (NIH) passed the ASME V&V 20 adequacy criterion at 95% confidence across all five operating points. Mesh convergence was confirmed with GCI < 1.5% for the NIH QoI. Model form uncertainty was quantified across three turbulence and two hemolysis model formulations; the selected model form minimizes validation discrepancy. Monte Carlo UQ with 10,000 samples confirms that the 95th percentile NIH prediction including all input uncertainties remains below the regulatory threshold (NIH_95 = 0.0087 g/100L versus threshold of 0.012 g/100L). Global Sobol sensitivity analysis identifies rotational speed and inlet flow rate as the dominant uncertainty contributors, both of which are tightly controlled in the COU. Software quality assurance, use error controls, and test sample adequacy all meet or exceed MRL 5 requirements. The provenance chain from raw experimental measurements through data reduction, simulation execution, and QoI extraction is complete and independently auditable. No credibility gaps or unresolved weakeners were identified. The assessment team concludes that the CFD model is sufficiently credible for its intended use in the regulatory submission supporting Class III CPB device approval.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
